or%20blocking%20solar%20heat%3A%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cul%3E%3Cli%3E%3Cstrong%3EInsulated%20window%20quilts%20or%20cellular%20shades.%3C%2Fstrong%3E%20Just%20as%20insulated%20shades%20can%20block%20heat%20from%20leaving%20your%20home%2C%20they%20can%20also%20keep%20it%20from%20getting%20in.%20You%20can%20increase%20their%20efficiency%20by%20keeping%20them%20tight%20around%20the%20edge%20of%20the%20window.%C2%A0%3C%2Fli%3E%3Cli%3E%3Cstrong%3ECurtains.%3C%2Fstrong%3E%20Hanging%20medium-colored%20%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fguides%2Fhome%2Fbest-blackout-curtains%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Ecurtains%3C%2Fa%3E%20with%20white%20backing%20%26quot%3Breduces%20heat%20gains%20by%2033%25%2C%26quot%3B%20according%20to%20DOE.%20They%20%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.nrel.gov%2Fdocs%2Flegosti%2Fold%2F15771.pdf%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Erecommend%3C%2Fa%3E%20choosing%20tightly%20woven%20fabrics%20in%20light%20colors%20to%20reflect%20sunlight.%20And%2C%20two%20layers%20of%20fabric%20is%20better%20than%20one.%20In%20a%20pinch%2C%20you%20can%20hang%20sheets%20or%20blankets%20over%20your%20windows%20as%20makeshift%20curtains.%3C%2Fli%3E%3Cli%3E%3Cstrong%3EWindow%20films.%20%3C%2Fstrong%3EWindow%20films%20help%20block%20ultraviolet%20rays%20from%20entering%20through%20windows%20and%20can%20reduce%20the%20amount%20of%20heat%20that%20comes%20through.%20You%20can%20find%20%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22nofollow%20noopener%20sponsored%20nofollow%20sponsored%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Faffiliate.insider.com%2F%3FamazonTrackingID%3Dbiauto-55230-20%26h%3D2bf86f28f7469522a95e55ee7446fdcf67e300fcd04f2c3789529ca8d28f6e96%26postID%3D628f975fa2374776c7e88141%26postSlug%3Dguides%252Fhome%252Fhow-to-cool-down-a-room%26tags%3Dservice%253Acapi%26u%3Dhttps%253A%252F%252Fwww.amazon.com%252FDaytime-Privacy-Non-Adhesive-Decorative-Control%252Fdp%252FB07P9Q4ZP8%252F%253Fth%253D1%5C%22%20data-autoaffiliated%3D%5C%22true%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Eclear%20or%20reflective%20window%20film%3C%2Fa%3E%20(reflective%20film%20will%20be%20more%20effective%20at%20driving%20heat%20away)%20in%20rolls%20that%20you%20can%20apply%20yourself.%C2%A0%3C%2Fli%3E%3Cli%3E%3Cstrong%3EExterior%20shutters%20or%20awnings.%3C%2Fstrong%3E%20Closed%20shutters%20keep%20much%20of%20the%20sun's%20heat%20from%20reaching%20windows%20in%20the%20first%20place.%20Awnings%20are%20also%20very%20effective%2C%20reducing%20heat%20gain%20from%20the%20summer%20sun%20by%20up%20to%2065%25%20on%20your%20home's%20south%20side%20and%20by%2077%25%20on%20the%20west-facing%20side.%20The%20DOE%20recommends%20choosing%20light-colored%20awnings%20to%20reflect%20the%20most%20sunlight.%3C%2Fli%3E%3C%2Ful%3E%5Cn%3Caside%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cstrong%3EQuick%20tip%3A%3C%2Fstrong%3E%20If%20your%20room%20is%20really%20in%20need%20of%20a%20cool%20down%20and%20it's%20cool%20enough%20outside%20to%20open%20a%20window%20(like%20at%20night%20or%20early%20morning)%20try%20hanging%20a%20wet%20sheet%20in%20front%20of%20the%20open%20window.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3C%2Faside%3E%5Cn%3Ch2%20data-toc-id%3D%5C%22d76bd7b5-a183-4109-8239-ea8ad1f0b48d%5C%22%3E%3Cstrong%3E5.%20Block%20air%20leaks%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3EAir%20can%20leak%20into%20and%20out%20of%20your%20house%20through%20even%20tiny%20openings%20around%20windows%2C%20doors%2C%20walls%2C%20and%20floors.%20This%20is%20not%20only%20a%20%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.nrel.gov%2Fdocs%2Ffy01osti%2F28039.pdf%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Ewaste%20of%20energy%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20but%20it%20can%20also%20devastate%20your%20attempts%20at%20keeping%20it%20cool.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EWeatherstripping%20and%20%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fguides%2Fhome%2Fhow-to-use-a-caulk-gun%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Ecaulking%3C%2Fa%3E%20can%20help%20prevent%20that%20precious%20cool%20air%20from%20escaping.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3ETo%20find%20out%20where%20air%20may%20be%20leaking%20in%20your%20home%2C%20inspect%20obvious%20spots%20where%20different%20materials%20meet%20%E2%80%94%20door%20frames%2C%20window%20frames%2C%20wall%20joints%2C%20and%20exterior%20bricks%2C%20stucco%2C%20or%20siding.%20Also%2C%20check%20where%20any%20exterior%20parts%20lead%20inside%2C%20such%20as%20around%20dryer%20vents%2C%20plumbing%2C%20and%20cable%20or%20internet%20lines.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EYou%20can%20also%20have%20a%20professional%20conduct%20a%20blower%20door%20test%20to%20help%20you%20specify%20where%20all%20your%20air%20leaks%20are.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%20data-toc-id%3D%5C%2249ea8e7e-f5be-4e9d-b3aa-eedf69ff9a8b%5C%22%3E%3Cstrong%3E6.%20Avoid%20using%20heat-emitting%20appliances%20and%20electronics%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3EAppliances%20like%20your%20dishwasher%2C%20oven%2C%20stove%2C%20washer%2C%20and%20dryer%20can%20emit%20a%20lot%20of%20heat%20when%20they're%20in%20use.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EAvoid%20using%20them%20if%20you%20can%20%E2%80%94%20especially%20during%20the%20hottest%20part%20of%20the%20day.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EIf%20you%20need%20to%20use%20one%20of%20these%20appliances%2C%20try%20shutting%20off%20the%20room%20to%20contain%20the%20heat%20and%20prevent%20it%20from%20spreading%20to%20the%20rest%20of%20your%20home.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EIf%20you%20have%20a%20computer%20that%20emits%20heat%2C%20shut%20it%20off.%20Also%20check%20your%20light%20bulbs.%20Incandescent%20bulbs%20can%20put%20off%20heat%2C%20so%20try%20to%20keep%20them%20turned%20off.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%20data-toc-id%3D%5C%2273f30eb9-b09f-4522-8376-53bd24eae270%5C%22%3E%3Cstrong%3E7.%20Use%20exhaust%20fans%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3EYou%20may%20not%20be%20able%20to%20use%20your%20gas%20range%2C%20but%20you%20should%20certainly%20use%20the%20exhaust%20hood%20above%20it.%20Turn%20it%20on%20to%20suck%20heat%20up%20and%20out.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EYou%20can%20also%20turn%20on%20your%20%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fnews.climate.columbia.edu%2F2018%2F08%2F03%2Fair-conditioning-keep-cool-heat-waves%2F%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Ebathroom%20fans%3C%2Fa%3E%20to%20help%20suck%20humid%2C%20warm%20air%20out.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%20data-toc-id%3D%5C%223491f6f2-a2a3-4c4f-9f7c-83eb53b3ef0c%5C%22%3E%3Cstrong%3E8.%20Focus%20efforts%20on%20your%20home's%20lowest%20level%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3ESince%20%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fscienceline.ucsb.edu%2Fgetkey.php%3Fkey%3D3901%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Ehot%20air%20rises%3C%2Fa%3E%20and%20cool%20air%20settles%2C%20you'll%20have%20an%20easier%20time%20keeping%20the%20lowest%20level%20of%20your%20home%20cool.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EIf%20you%20have%20a%20cooler%20lower%20level%2C%20you%20can%20use%20it%20to%20ventilate%20your%20entire%20home.%20If%20there's%20a%20cool%20breeze%20outside%2C%20you%20can%20open%20windows%20on%20the%20lower%20levels%20to%20encourage%20the%20air%20to%20flow%20in.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThen%2C%20open%20windows%20on%20the%20upper%20level%20to%20create%20a%20vacuum%20and%20encourage%20the%20rising%20hot%20air%20to%20flow%20out.%20This%20is%20what%20the%20DOE%20refers%20to%20as%20the%20%26quot%3B%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.energy.gov%2Fenergysaver%2Fnatural-ventilation%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Echimney%20effect%3C%2Fa%3E.%26quot%3B%20If%20you%20have%20fans%2C%20you%20can%20use%20them%20to%20speed%20up%20the%20process.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EIf%20your%20lower%20level%20is%20a%20basement%20with%20no%20windows%2C%20try%20setting%20up%20a%20fan%20in%20the%20doorway%20toward%20the%20rest%20of%20your%20home%20and%20opening%20upper%20windows%20to%20let%20rising%20hot%20air%20out.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20DOE%20notes%20that%20this%20method%20works%20best%20in%20dry%20climates%20and%20at%20cooler%20times%20of%20day.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%20data-toc-id%3D%5C%22597a794b-8d6e-4f0c-9b6d-15f03305bb4b%5C%22%3E%3Cstrong%3E9.%20Dehumidify%20your%20room%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3EWhile%20humid%20heat%20is%20%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.12news.com%2Farticle%2Fnews%2Fverify%2Fverify-does-dry-or-humid-heat-really-matter-when-it-comes-to-heat-exhaustion%2F75-3d63f623-bd7a-4c4c-90ac-714c9e9d9011%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Enot%20necessarily%20more%20deadly%3C%2Fa%3E%20than%20dry%20heat%2C%20it%20does%20affect%20how%20your%20body%20cools%20itself.%20When%20moisture%20levels%20in%20the%20air%20are%20high%2C%20it%20makes%20it%20%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fresearch.noaa.gov%2Farticle%2FArtMID%2F587%2FArticleID%2F2621%2FDangerous-humid-heat-extremes-occurring-decades-before-expected%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Emore%20difficult%3C%2Fa%3E%20for%20your%20sweat%20to%20evaporate.%20The%20evaporation%20of%20sweat%20is%20imperative%20for%20body%20temperature%20regulation.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Caside%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cstrong%3ENote%3A%3C%2Fstrong%3E%20According%20to%20the%20EPA%2C%20it's%20best%20to%20keep%20your%20home%20below%2060%25%20humidity%2C%20and%20ideally%20between%2030%25%20and%2050%25.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3C%2Faside%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EYou%20can%20dehumidify%20a%20room%20by%20purchasing%20a%20dehumidifier.%20If%20you%20don't%20have%20a%20dehumidifier%2C%20these%20methods%20can%20help%20%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.epa.gov%2Fmold%2Fbrief-guide-mold-moisture-and-your-home%23tab-6%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Ereduce%20moisture%20in%20the%20air%3C%2Fa%3E%3A%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cul%3E%3Cli%3EOpen%20windows%2C%20but%20only%20if%20it's%20cool%20enough%20outside.%3C%2Fli%3E%3Cli%3ETurn%20on%20fans%20to%20help%20evaporate%20moisture.%3C%2Fli%3E%3Cli%3EWhen%20showering%2C%20run%20your%20bathroom%20fan%2C%20open%20a%20window%2C%20or%20simply%20take%20cooler%20showers%20that%20don't%20put%20off%20as%20much%20steam.%3C%2Fli%3E%3Cli%3EIf%20you%20see%20condensation%20on%20windows%20or%20other%20surfaces%2C%20this%20is%20a%20sign%20of%20high%20humidity.%20Wipe%20it%20away%20with%20a%20towel%20and%20try%20to%20find%20the%20source%20of%20the%20moisture.%3C%2Fli%3E%3C%2Ful%3E%5Cn%3Caside%3E%5Cn%3Ch2%20data-toc-id%3D%5C%22cdcc895f-9e5a-4ed8-bbc6-f9c9c2e46dc1%5C%22%3EBest%20dehumidifiers%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cfigure%3E%3Cimg%20width%3D%5C%221484%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22An%20Ivation%2050-Pint%20Dehumidifier%20sits%20in%20a%20white-walled%20room%20next%20to%20a%20table%20with%20a%20kettle%20and%20near%20an%20armchair%2C%20one%20of%20the%20best%20dehumidifeirs%20in%202022.%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F6287dd16b0a8be00185fd191%3Fformat%3Djpeg%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%221113%5C%22%3E%3Cfigcaption%3E%3Cp%3ETarget%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3E%3Cp%3ERemove%20excess%20humidity%20from%20the%20air%20with%20one%20of%20the%20%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fguides%2Fhome%2Fbest-dehumidifier%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Ebest%20dehumidifiers%3C%2Fa%3E%20we've%20tested%2C%20which%20can%20also%20help%20to%20prevent%20mold%20and%20mildew%20growth.%C2%A0%3Cbr%3E%3Cbr%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cul%3E%3Cli%3E%3Cstrong%3EBest%20overall%3A%20%3C%2Fstrong%3EHomeLabs%20Dehumidifier%20-%20%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22nofollow%20noopener%20sponsored%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Faffiliate.insider.com%2F%3FamazonTrackingID%3Dbiauto-55230-20%26h%3D439ee3e9a2c8c6ca54745035620475e9b7a682cfa2fe4ac71805c85958f00343%26postID%3D628f975fa2374776c7e88141%26postSlug%3Dguides%252Fhome%252Fhow-to-cool-down-a-room%26tags%3Dservice%253Acapi%26u%3Dhttps%253A%252F%252Fwww.amazon.com%252Fdp%252FB073V9MG3Y%5C%22%20data-autoaffiliated%3D%5C%22true%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3ESee%20at%20Amazon%3C%2Fa%3E%3C%2Fli%3E%3Cli%3E%3Cstrong%3EBest%20for%20large%20spaces%3A%20%3C%2Fstrong%3EIvation%204%2C500-Square-Foot%20Dehumidifier%20-%20See%20at%20%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22nofollow%20noopener%20sponsored%5C%22%20href%3D%5